t1448.text: And like Marie Kondo, try to thank these people for their friendship and say goodbye when the right time comes.

t1449.text: You just need to accept that your friendship is not going to be the same again, or in extreme cases, that you need to put an end to it. And again, this is fine - choosing to end a bad friendship because you know it isn't right is a responsible thing for you to do for you.

t1450.text: And sometimes that doesn't pan out - sometimes you realise that the person they were before no longer aligns with your values, your humour, your way of life; or that you no longer align with theirs, and that might be a wake-up call but y'know... that's okay.

t1451.text: I think it's a misconception that we're relieved when friendships that seem so comfortable even after months or years of not talking is BECAUSE the person hasn't changed. Rather, it's that we are relieved because even though that person HAS changed you can still get on with them.

t1452.text: It's weird when people ask me advice about how to navigate friendships with people who've changed... like, have you yourself not changed or are unwilling to accept that people will continue to grow and change heedless of your own growth or lack thereof?
